<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>pencan  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 1993  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="pencan"> canonical form of matrix pencil  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[Q,M,i1]=pencan(Fs)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[Q,M,i1]=pencan(E,A)  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>Fs  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : a regular pencil <VERB>s*E-A</VERB>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>E,A  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : two real square matrices
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>Q,M  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : two non-singular real matrices
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>i1  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : integer
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    Given the regular pencil <VERB>Fs=s*E-A</VERB>, <VERB>pencan</VERB> returns matrices <VERB>Q</VERB> 
    and <VERB>M</VERB>
    such than <VERB>M*(s*E-A)*Q</VERB> is in &quot;canonical&quot; form.
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>M*E*Q</VERB> is a block matrix 
  </P>
  <VERBATIM><![CDATA[
[I,0;
 0,N]
   ]]></VERBATIM>
  <P>
    with <VERB>N</VERB> nilpotent and <VERB>i1</VERB> = size of the <VERB>I</VERB> matrix above.
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>M*A*Q</VERB> is a block matrix:
  </P>
  <VERBATIM><![CDATA[
[Ar,0;
 0,I]
   ]]></VERBATIM>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
F=randpencil([],[1,2],[1,2,3],[]);
F=rand(6,6)*F*rand(6,6);
[Q,M,i1]=pencan(F);
W=clean(M*F*Q)
roots(det(W(1:i1,1:i1)))
det(W($-2:$,$-2:$))
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
